    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix file descriptor leak in ITTI task initialization and cleanup\n\n### Summary\nThere is a file descriptor leak where an opened fd is not closed on error paths downstream of function timer_setup in common/utils/ocp_itti/intertask_interface.cpp.\n\nThe leak occurs in two scenarios:\n1. When epoll_ctl fails during task initialization in itti_create_queue, the epoll_fd and sem_fd file descriptors are not closed before program termination\n2. When tasks are destroyed, the file descriptors are not properly closed, leading to resource leaks over time\n\nThis fix ensures proper cleanup of file descriptors in error paths and adds a task destruction function to handle resource cleanup.\n\n### Changes\n- `common/utils/ocp_itti/intertask_interface.cpp`: \n  * Added proper error handling in itti_create_queue to close file descriptors if epoll_ctl fails\n  * Added itti_destroy_task function to properly close file descriptors when tasks are destroyed\n  * Added necessary headers for file operations and error handling\n- `common/utils/ocp_itti/intertask_interface.h`: \n  * Added declaration for itti_destroy_task function\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Initialize multiple ITTI tasks in a long-running application\n2. Monitor file descriptor usage with lsof or similar tools\n3. Observe that file descriptors accumulate over time and are not released when tasks are terminated\n4. In error conditions during task initialization, observe that epoll file descriptors remain open even after program termination\n\nThe fix can be verified by monitoring file descriptor usage before and after the changes, ensuring that file descriptors are properly closed when tasks are destroyed or when initialization fails.\n"
}